A census-designated place (CDP) in Southeast Fairbanks Census Area, Alaska, United States.

A river in northern California and southwestern Oregon in the United States, approximately 113 km long. The river flows within an enclosed basin on the volcanic plateau southwest of the Klamath River watershed. It rises in two forks in northern Modoc County, California west of Goose Lake in the Modoc National Forest. The short North Fork and South Fork, each approximately 32 km long, flow west and join east of the Clear Lake Reservoir. The combined stream flows through the Clear Lake Reservoir, then flows in a northward loop through southern Klamath County, Oregon, re-entering California approximately 32 km southeast of Klamath Falls. It enters the north end of intermittent Tule Lake, approximately 13 km south of the Oregon-California border.

A short intermittent river on the Pacific coast of southern California in the United States, approximately 80 km long. One of the last free-flowing rivers in southern California, it drains an arid region of the Coast Ranges between Los Angeles and San Diego at the southern end of the Santa Ana Mountains. It is formed in southwestern Riverside County, east of Interstate 15 25 km ENE of Temecula, from the confluence of Temecula Creek and Murrieta Creek. It flows southwest past Temecula, through the Temecula Canyon at the south end of the Santa Ana Mountains. Along its lower 16 km the river forms a large floodplain as it crosses Camp Pendleton Marine Corps Base. It enters the Gulf of Santa Catalina on the Pacific approximately 5 km northwest of Oceanside.

A river located in southern California in the United States. It drains an area of the coastal mountains north of Los Angeles. Its headwaters are near the town of Acton in Los Angeles County, on the north slope of the San Gabriel Mountains. It flows along the north side of the Santa Susana Mountains and empties into the Pacific Ocean between the cities of Ventura and Oxnard, in the area designated by the state as the Santa Clara River Estuary Natural Reserve in the Oxnard Plain.

A river in Ventura County, California. The river forms at the confluence of Matilija Creek and North Fork Matilija Creek, 15 miles upstream from the Pacific Ocean. San Antonio Creek joins the river halfway to the ocean and Coyote Creek does the same a couple of miles downstream. However, the flow from Coyote Creek has not been very large since the completion of Casitas Dam, which forms Lake Casitas.

A river on the Central Coast of California is formed at the confluence of the Sisquoc River and Cuyama River, just east of the city of Santa Maria about 32 km from its delta at the Pacific Ocean. The entire river defines the north/south border of Santa Barbara and San Luis Obispo County up to the Sisquoc River.

A coastal river in Monterey County in the State of California. It is formed by the confluence of its North and Middle Forks, at an elevation of roughly 390 m. The North Fork is the longer of the two streams, beginning at an elevation of 1,050 m. and running in a straight course southward to where it joins the Middle Fork. The smaller Middle Fork begins at an elevation of 970 m and flows south-southwest to meet the North Fork and form the mainstem of McWay Creek. After the mainstem is formed, the creek winds south and west through a narrow canyon to where it meets the South Fork at an elevation of roughly1 20 m. The South Fork, the largest sub-basin in the McWay Creek watershed, begins at an elevation of 780 m on the east side of a ridge that separates it from the mainstem. After flowing south and turning slightly in a south-southwest direction, it meets McWay Creek. The creek then heads southwest, passing a parking area for Julia Pfeiffer Burns State Park and crossing underneath Highway 1 in a concrete culvert. It spills into the Pacific Ocean at Waterfall Cove.
A river on the Central Coast of California.

A river on the Central Coast of California. The Little Sur River has a South Fork and a North Fork. Both have their headwaters in the Santa Lucias, straddling Pico Blanco mountain. The forks meet about two miles before the river empties into the Pacific Ocean. The South Fork travels roughly northeast and the North Fork roughly east, with large bends to the north and south.
A river that originates in the Santa Lucia Mountains, flows northwest through the Carmel Valley and empties into the Pacific Ocean south of Carmel-by-the-Sea.

A river in Northern California, forming part of the border between Santa Cruz County and Monterey County and between San Benito County and Santa Clara County. Its headwaters are in the Diablo Range, from which the river flows west for 30 miles, passing the city of Watsonville and discharging to Monterey Bay. The San Benito River joins the river about 15 miles upstream from the ocean. San Felipe Lake, also called Upper Soap Lake, is a permanent lake on the upper reaches of the river, upstream of its meeting with the San Benito River. Lower Soap Lake, also called Soap Lake, is an intermittent body of water a few miles downstream of the upper lake.

A large perennial river in the San Francisco Bay Area. The creek runs for 72 km from a lake northeast of Packard Ridge to the eastern shore San Francisco Bay by way of Niles Canyon and a flood control channel. Two-thirds of the watershed is in Alameda County including the reach through the Sunol Valley, the rest is in Santa Clara County. The tributaries of Alameda creek include Arroyo de la Laguna, Arroyo del Valle, San Antonio Creek and Calaveras Creek, whose main tributary is Arroyo Hondo.

One of the principal creeks which runs out of the Berkeley Hills in the East Bay area of the San Francisco Bay Area in California. In its upper stretch, it passes entirely within the city limits of Berkeley, and marks the city limit with the adjacent city of Albany in its lower section. It enters San Francisco Bay into what remains of a once much larger slough adjacent to Golden Gate Fields racetrack.
A river. Discharges to San Francisco Bay.

A river that flows into San Francisco Bay in California, United States of America. Its headwaters are in the Santa Cruz Mountains above Menlo Park, around 667 m above the Bay. Its major tributaries are called Bear Creek and Corte Madera Creek (both common names for creeks in California). These merge at the Searsville Lake in the Jasper Ridge Biological Preserve.

A river that drains a large watershed in Santa Cruz County, California. The headwaters originate in the Santa Cruz Mountains (in Castle Rock State Park) at an elevation of 2500 feet and flow approximately 30 miles through the San Lorenzo Valley before discharging to the Pacific Ocean at Monterey Bay.

A river in Santa Cruz and San Mateo counties in California. It is the longest stream in San Mateo County and flows all year from springs in the Santa Cruz Mountains. Its headwaters are near Portola Redwoods State Park and it drains most of that state park, with Peters Creek being one of its largest tributaries.
A river in San Mateo County, California.
A river.
A coastal stream in San Mateo County, California, USA, that rises on the western slopes of the Santa Cruz Mountains and discharges to the Pacific Ocean at Pilarcitos Creek Beach.

A coastal river in western San Mateo County, California. Arroyo de en Medio rises on the western slopes of Montara Mountain and discharges to the Pacific Ocean at Half Moon Bay at the location of the unincorporated community of Miramar at Miramar Beach.
A principal river in San Mateo County, California and carries a large amount of the runoff of the Santa Cruz Mountains into the Pacific Ocean through the delta at its mouth Pescadero Marsh.
A river in the Rockaway Beach and Vallemar neighborhoods of Pacifica, California.
A small river in San Mateo County, California.

A river. It flows toward the San Francisco Bay from near San Bruno Mountain. Its small delta is just in between South San Francisco and the San Francisco International Airport.

A coastal river in western San Mateo County, California. Denniston Creek rises on the western slopes of Montara Mountain and discharges to the Pacific Ocean at Pillar Point Harbor somewhat north of El Granada Beach.
A river.
A river. It rises 2.1 km north of Sierra Morena and flows westward to the Pacific Ocean 3.7 km south-southeast of Miramontes Point.
A river, in the Rockaway Beach neighborhood of Pacifica, California. Located just south of Calera Creek.
A river in San Mateo County, California, USA that rises on the western slopes of the Santa Cruz Mountains and discharges to the Pacific Ocean at Naples Beach.
A coastal river whose watershed lies entirely within San Mateo County, California, United States on the western exposures of the Montara mountain block, discharging to the Pacific Ocean.
A river. It discharges into South San Francisco Bay. The Port of Redwood City, the largest deepwater port in South San Francisco Bay, is situated on the east bank of Redwood Creek near its mouth.
A river.

A perennial river in the City of Pacifica, San Mateo County, California in the San Francisco Bay Area which runs from the Santa Cruz Mountains in the Golden Gate National Recreation Area through the San Pedro Valley, which it formed through erosion to its mouth near Shelter Cove of the Pacific Ocean.
An intermittent river that rises on the eastern slopes of the Northern Santa Cruz Mountains in San Mateo County, California, USA.
A river.
A river in western Contra Costa County, California running through the town of Pinole, California and discharging to the San Francisco Bay.
A river in central Contra Costa County, California.
A river in Contra Costa County, California which drains into the Carquinez Strait by way of the Arroyo del Hambre. It descends through the Briones Valley to the city of Martinez.
A river in Richmond, California's Hilltop neighborhood. It runs into the San Pablo Bay.

A three-branch river in Richmond and El Cerrito, California, United States forming the Baxter Creek watershed. The creek has three sources and flows from the Berkeley Hills to Stege Marsh and the San Francisco Bay.
One of the principal watercourses running out of the Berkeley Hills into San Francisco Bay in northern California. It defines part of the boundary between Alameda County and Contra Costa County.

A river inwestern Contra Costa County, California which empties into San Pablo Bay south of Point Pinole. The creek rises from Rolling Hills Cemetery and passes through Rollingwood, the campus of Contra Costa Community College, and the city of San Pablo, California.
